videoTitle: Oilfield Service Job
videoDescription: short #shorts #rig #ad #drilling #oil #tripping #derrickman #Floorman #Toolphusher #derrickman #oilfeild #drilling #explore ...
commentText: Done that in the 80s, used 24" pipe wrenchs to put them in and occasionally a 36" manually operated single tooth, pipe tong to break them loose coming out. Doped every collar going in mostly 2000' old stripper wells.  Climb the mast and get traveling block out of lift by retrieving end hook.  So we could single line rods going back in the hole.  So hot one summer, I had to bring an electric fan to keep from overheating, glad they had a electric jack on that well, no shade and no wind blowing.  Wrenched, walked rods and pipe out one day and put it all back in the next day.  The owner drove and worked the draw works, I would stake all the guy lines with a 16lb sledgehammer that would start rolling 2" tubing if it hit a rock.  About 30 years old, and weighted 155 pounds.   .

videoTitle: Working a Construction Job
commentText: Im one of the few that got out.  Took the job offer from my uncle when i was 17, worked there for a year and a half while going to night school, loved it at first.  The only issue is working with my uncle sucks, hes the type to put others down to make himself look good and can never be wrong.  It was the same with one of the old guys there, the young generations is so weak willed and never wants to do shit, all i had to hear everyday at lunch.  Started eating in my truck every day, talking a lot less, just putting earbuds and going to work, i liked the hanging with the other guys my age, we were all in the same boat somewhat but they were a couple years older so they werent completely relateable.  It got to the point of me dreading waking up and going to work, not because of hard it was, the 11 hour shift and then going to school for 3 or 4 hours, it wasnt the shoveling gravels for 9 hours straight at 103F outside, it was the fact i had to get up and deal with those assholes for hours.  I finally finished night school and put in my 2 weeks to get ready for college to get my bachelors to become a therapist, it was the great 2 months of my life being free from everything for once.  My college plan has since fell through since i had to leave to take care of my mom but im a lot happier than i was then.

videoTitle: Silicon Valley Moved to Austin. Then Regretted It.
videoDescription: Austin saw the biggest price drop in homes in the United States. So what's happening to the city that was luring Silicon Valley?
commentText: I grew up in the Bay Area and lived in Dallas for a year. I visited Austin, San Antonio, Houston, Galveston. I‚Äôll never set foot in Texas again if I can possibly help it. I knew a lot of people who moved there from the Bay Area would regret it. There just isn‚Äôt enough to do within easy access for enough of the year. In the Bay Area, you can take a day trip to go skiiing from December until March. You can sail or kayak or windsurf the rest of the year from scores of launches along the Bay and all along the Delta. You can comfortably hike year round, play tennis outdoors, bike in Golden Gate Park. In Dallas, I couldn‚Äôt do anything outdoors during the summertime. It was 90 degrees at night. I know Austin wasn‚Äôt any more comfortable. Stanford and Cal are two of the best universities in the world, creating a stimulating, invigorating environment. Unfortunately, Oakland has lost its professional sports franchises, but you still have the 49ers, Giants, Warriors, Sharks and Earthquakes, all the major sports. Austin? None of them. The food is better, world famous in San Francisco. More variety, fresh fruit and vegetables year round, pretty cheap too. There‚Äôs just no comparison in my mind. Sure real estate might have been cheaper, and probably still is, but I don‚Äôt want to stay indoors looking at the walls all day. More space just means more space to clean. A bigger garden means more weeds to pull. A riding lawn mower is not as much fun as a kayak. People severely misjudged what life in Texas is like.  So I‚Äôll tell you. it sucks. Austin and the surrounding Hill Country are the nicest parts, but Texas as a whole sucks, especially with the current gubmint.

commentText: It's true that the shifts in work arrangements are creating some very real ripples, and we're seeing that play out right here in Dallas. It's truly disheartening to hear about people you know facing the difficult decision of selling their homes, sometimes at a lower price than they purchased them for, all to relocate closer to their company's office.  Many employers are indeed making it clear that a return to in-office work is becoming a requirement, and for those who had moved further out for the flexibility of remote work, this can present a significant challenge. It forces a tough choice between their current living situation and their job security.

They have no idea what people will do to each other to get promoted,  to get that special detail, to get that detective position. People would always say to me, "you guys don't get paid enough..." You are correct. But not for the reasons you think. I carried a gun, wore body armor and was trained to deal with all sorts of threats from domestic encounters, three hundred pound drunks, meth heads and active shooters. But there is no armor, no training that can protect you from a weaponized administration. The world would be shocked at the things I have seen.  But now I have a nice job and get a check every month from my department's retirement that reminds me that I don't have those problems any more.   All the best, young lady.  You got out alive.

commentText: Ex-truck driver here.   I drove Cents Per Mile, owner operator and lease operator. OTR.   It not very profitable.   -owner operator. If you buy a brand new truck, your expenses go towards the truck payment, trailer payment (which is another expense), insurance for both truck and trailer, insurance for the loads, fuel for both truck and trailer, IFTA,  Tolls (east coast tolls are absurdly expensive) . Plus,  repair schedules. Also, depends highly on what the market offers and other factors. Sure, you can earn 350k - 450k gross per year. BUT, with all of those expenses  you will net under 60k per year. And then you're taxed on personal income.  If you buy USED equipment, the same as above applies, except now there are major pending issues, repairs, and preventive  maintenance. Your equipment will become a risk factor. -Cpm (cent per mile) you can earn 50-75 cents per mile, but most  if not all, companies have you running from zipcode to zipcode basis instead of per mile. You have no control on maintenance and no control on basically anything. And then escrow gets removed, also, personal tax at 33%.  -lease operator is almost a hybrid of both owner and CPM, just depending of the clauses being signed for at the beginning of your contract agreements.  The only and best way to make good money is if you own a company and have everyone else work for you,  take no executive decisions with 200+ trucks, have your own shop, have your own insurance firm and have PRISTINE, loyal and fully dedicated drivers under your belt. But, that is just a dream.

You could also work for a mega carrier (Big Fleet companies like Swift, CR England, knight, etc.) and eventually become a trainer. commentText: The snowfall wasn't what caused the power outage in 2021. It was the temperatures getting down into the single digits for multiple days. Colder areas are better prepared for this, but in Texas most people have either natural gas or electric heating, primarily heat pumps. The problem with heat pumps, and why they're not relied on heavily in colder areas, is that they're only effective down to about 20¬∫F. Below that, they switch into "emergency heating" which is a form of resistance heating and only about 20-25% as efficient as a heat pump. So the grid saw a massive spike in energy usage in a small timeframe. Something that doesn't happen in colder areas where people would never consider using electrical resistance heating as it's too expensive.

commentText: Ive lived in CT my whole life, and when i was 20 i worked at a gas stationas an assistant manager. One day my boss put a hiring sign in the front window and i asked her how many people we were loking to hire. She told me zero. Appsrently around 2010 CT created a law stating that all companies had to advertise that they were hiring. Part of that law was that no one could be denied an application if the store used paper ones, if not you had to explain to the person how to apply online. It was supposedly meant to help decrease all types of prejudice during the hiring process. It made no sense to me because if a manager was prejudice, that persn they didnt like would never make it past the first interview. Anyways, all it did was fool people into thinking we were actually hiring when we werent. It wasted everyone involved time. I tried explaining the law to people when they would come back in or call about the application they dropped off weeks ago. People were pissed. I was mad because i had to keep dealing with everyone who was upset.

commentText: Part of it, I believe I've heard, is to make it look like they are hiring, even getting applications, so when an employee asks for a raise, they can point to the listings only to say that they have hundreds of people looking to get the employee's job. That they should be grateful for what they have and that they can replace them on a whim. Sure, they possibly could, however, that doesn't account for training, the risk of a new hire possibly not fitting in or being even more of a pain to work with, and they already have as few people hired as possible, so they don't want to fire you, because even if they get a replacement, that's a role that's not going to be functioning properly, if at all for a while when you're gone. But they can always threaten you and make you feel replaceable so you don't ask for a raise, or potentially even take a pay cut.  Manipulation is standard practice in a capitalist system.

commentText: If you are applying for jobs you should expect 9 out of 10 jobs to be ghost jobs or required postings. If the job has little more then a title, likely a ghost job. If the posting has a very eclectic mix of requirements likely a required post tailored to the person pre-selected to fill it. If a generally cohesive wish list with few requirements, that likely a real job. General 10-20 applications per interview and 10-20 interviews to get hired. I have successfully done this 3 times, once for an entry level job and twice for student level jobs. All the other jobs used industry contacts, recruiters, and general back channel shenanigans. If you are not networking it's almost impossible to get employed üòï And at some point when you get higher in your career they don't post jobs or even have them. It is more about having a contact in a company that is growing and can create a position for you. But that's VP level positions and while I have had spots created for me it is not common at my level and some of that may have, honestly, been DEI opportunity for the company.

commentText: And then there is the increasing prevalence of things called MUDs (Municipal Utility District), suburban new developments that are on the outside of a city limit, and ouside of that nearest town's water, sewer, drainage, emergency services, etc.  Because they have to contract with the nearest town,  the MUD has to charge a fee to cover those costs, and also the costs sustained when the new suddivision conne ted to the town.  Unfortunately , too many people don't even know that their new house is located in an MUD till after they've moved in.  That is because the postal address for a subdivision could say something like Katy or Georgetown and still be outside of the city limits.  The utility costs for homeowners who live in MUD's can be astronomical, AND they can assess their own property tax.  In fact , for a person with a $300,000 house , the annual MUD tax could be as much as $2700.  If you are thinking of buying a house in suburban Texas , make sure to ask about this.

commentText: MUD utilities will cost you big time.  Most do not allow tax exemptions for homestead or over 65.  The developer will create the district, spend a fortune on infrastructure with no real regard to cost because they know they get reimbursed by the MUD taxes collected from the homeowners.  Developer charges interest on the monies spent until repaid from bonds issued, and those bonds will require repayment (typically) in 30yrs.  In my neighborhood, the MUD tax on a 2200sqft home appraised at $440K is almost $4K per year.  Just for utility taxes.  Add county, school, emergency services, road and bridge, and you are quickly looking at $13K per year in property taxes, and that on top of the mortgage.

videoTitle: how we‚Äôre *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.
